Exploring the Realtionship between Spotify Stream Count Over Time and a Song's Attributes: By Mohini Yadav and Erin Nell¶

Project Overview¶

Datsets

We will be conducting an analysis on the following two datasets:

Spotify Songs Streamed 2023 Dataset:

This dataset reports the songs with the most streams of the Spotify streaming platform as of 2023. Aside from stream count on Spotify, it includes the song title, artist, and additional details like the attributes of the song. For example, the song's danceability, speechiness, and valence. This attributes are measured on a scale from 0.0-1.0. We later convert this to a percentage scale from 0-100%. Each attribute is calculated by analyzing different aspects of the song. Throughout our analysis we will come to analyze the following attributes:

  1. Danceability: Measures how likely someone is to dance to a song. This is based off of various elements, such as tempo, rhythm stability, beat strength, and overall regularity. It is measured on a scale of 0.0 is least danceable and 1.0 is most danceable.
  2. Speechiness: Detects the amount of spoken words in a song. A track on spotify with a measure of 1.0 is only spoken word, most likely an audio book. Values between 0.33 and 0.66 include both music and spoken word, such as rap songs. And tracks belwo 0.33 are most likely types of music without spoken words.
  3. Valence: Measures the songs positivity. Tracks closer to 1.0. sound more positive, such as happy or cheerful. Tracks closer to 0.0 sound negative, such as sad, depressed, or angry. In general, Spotify measures this using a set of agreed upon notions of what happy or positive music sounds like.

For further reading on how other attributes are measured in the dataset, see Spotify's list of audio features. This dataset also includes intrastic statiststics on a song's performance on other streaming platforms, such as Apple Music or Deezer.

Spotify Songs Streamed 2024 Dataset:

This dataset reports the songs with the most streams on Spotify in 2024. Note that this is cumulative and is the songs stream count from its release to 2024, not just for the year of 2024. Like the dataset for 2023, it includes a track title, the artist, and the stream count on Spotify. In addition, it includes a song's performance on social media platforms like TikTok and YouTube. This dataset does not include data on a track's attributes but does include whether or not the track is explicit.

Note, both of these datasets were obtained from Kaggle and made by the same author.

Motivation

We believe that working with Spotify streaming data presents a unique opportunity to further understand market insights and song performance. Analyzing streaming data helps us understand current music trends, and evolving listener preferences. This insight can be valuable for artists, producers, and marketers in the music industry. For example, the ability to predict which songs are likely to gain more streams could influence how artists, labels, and platforms market songs, curate playlists, and tailor recommendations. With song performance, understanding which songs perform best on streaming platforms can inform marketing strategies and decisions on which songs to promote.

Our analysis also highlights how data science can be used to uncover insights and trends in music behavior. Moreover, how data science methods can be applied beyond traditional fields, showing their broad applicability to music data

Through data science techniques, this notebook will explore relationships between the attributes of songs, such as liveliness, danceability, and valence, and and the growth of a songs stream count over time. We use linear regression modeling to understand whether the relationship between the two, and the accuracy of whether a song's stream count can be predicted with one attribute versus having all the attribute. Furthermore, this notebooks includes further analysis of our datasets, showing correlation and identifying songs with the largest growth in stream count. This analysis can be used as the foundation for further analysis into what effects a song's continued growth on streaming platforms such as Spotify.

Research Questions

Throughout the analysis, our guiding research questions were:

  1. Can we use the Spotify stream count to understand why some songs remain the most streamed?

  2. Specifically, do attributes such as valence, speechiness, or danceability relate to a song's stream count over time?

  3. Can we use these attributes to predict a songs growth in streams from 2023-24?

We are going to join the datsets by the song and artist and tidy the data so we can draw conclusions during our analysis. Note, that we are creating a new column, 'stream_change', which is found by subtracting 'streams_2024' and 'streams_2023' to find the total streaming count growth for a song that appears on both datasets. This will effectively allow us to see which songs performed the best over time for 2023-24.

In [411]:
df2023 = df
df2024 = df_tidy2024

# standardizing the column names for when we merge
df2023.rename(columns={'track_name': 'song', 'artist(s)_name': 'artist'}, inplace=True)
df2024.rename(columns={'Track': 'song', 'Artist': 'artist'}, inplace=True)

# merging the the dataframes based on an inner join so we only get songs that appear both in 2023 and 2024
merged_dfs = pd.merge(df2023, df2024, on=['song', 'artist'], how='inner')

# dropping columns we dont need
merged_dfs = merged_dfs.drop(columns=['Release Date', 'Album Name', 'All Time Rank', 'Spotify Popularity', 'Track Score'])

# renaming based on year
merged_dfs.rename(columns={'streams': 'streams_2023', 'Spotify Streams': 'streams_2024'}, inplace=True)

# add new column which shows the difference between the stream count by year
merged_dfs['stream_change'] = merged_dfs['streams_2024'] - merged_dfs['streams_2023']

# remove songs with a negative stream change since that is impossible and means the stream count was entered in incorrectly
merged_dfs = merged_dfs[merged_dfs['stream_change'] >= 0]

# creating a new column order so (spotify) streams are next to each other
new_column_order = ['song', 'artist', 'artist_count', 'released_year', 'streams_2023', 'streams_2024', 'stream_change',
                    'bpm', 'danceability_%', 'valence_%', 'energy_%', 'acousticness_%', 'instrumentalness_%',
                    'liveness_%', 'speechiness_%', 'Explicit Track']
merged_dfs = merged_dfs[new_column_order]

# if there are duplicates, so keep first occurence of the duplicate
merged_dfs = merged_dfs[~merged_dfs['song'].duplicated(keep='first')]

merged_dfs.head()

Correlations Between Attributes and Stream Growth

A heatmap is going to be a good way to quickly gauge the correlation between different variables. We see that variables like speechiness, valence, and danceability have negative correlations to stream_change and that is weak, but still substantial. This information will provide the foundation for our models, in that we believe that there is some correlation between these attributes (our independent variables) and stream change (the dependent variable). Also, interestingly, there is a moderate correlation between danceability and valence. The relationship between the rest of the independent variables to each other (speechiness and valence, danceability and speechiness, etc.) show a relatively week correlation.

Comparing Average Speechiness, Danceability, and Valence for the Top 10 Songs Versus All Songs:

Now that we see that there is a negative correlation between the variables, we want to get a better idea of how this is reflected in our data. Lets see the average speechiness, danceability, and valence in the data and what this posibily means and break down our analysis:

  1. Speechiness_%: we see that for the all the songs from this dataset, the average speechiness is 9.2%. As this falls below 33% we can assume these songs are not of the rap genre. Furthermore, the top 10 songs have a lower average speechiness of 5.5%, meaning that there may be a correlation between fewer spoken words and better performance.
  2. Danceability_%: The top 10 songs also have a lower average danceability than the average for all the songs on the playlist. However, does this mean that songs perform best with an average danceability of 57%, or is this average possible swayed by an outlier. Further analysis will be performed. Despite this, all songs and the top 10 songs have an average danceability of above 50%, this may hit that danceable songs perform better.
  3. Valence_%: the average valence for the top 10 songs is lower than the average for all of the songs on the dataset. We can infer that perhaps a song does not to be super positive to perform well. We will perform further analysis to see if the average for the top 10 songs is swayed by outliers.

Overall, we can see that the averages for these attributes falls relatively closely to the averages for all the songs on the dataset. This suggests that these attributes might influence a song's performance, but further statistical analysis is needed to confirm their significance. For further analysis, we will perform models to test our hypothesis as our last steps.

Let's check if Billie Eilish's song could be considered an outlier. For a simple way to check, we use the inter quartile range (IQR) and see if the average valence_% for this song falls within the its upper and lower bounds. For more reading on this method, click here. From our calculations, we see that the bounds of the IQR are (-7.875, 101.125). With a valence_% of 14, the song What Was I Made For? falls within these bounds and is not considered an outlier. Thus, we can assume that a song does not have to be positive to perform well and that the average valence of the top 10 songs is not being skewed by this one song. In fact, 6 out of 10 of these songs fall below the valence of 50% line, meaning majority of these top 10 songs are not extremely positive and gearing towards negative.

In [431]:
# calculate Q1 (25th percentile) and Q3 (75th percentile) for valence_% in top 10 songs

# calculate the IQR

lower_bound = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR

Linear Regression Models¶

We plan to use danceability, valence, and speechiness (independent variables) to predict the growth of a song's streams (stream_count, dependent variable). Thus, we will use a multiple linear regression model first to see if the independent variables will be good predictors of the dependent variable.

In [432]:
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression
from sklearn.metrics import r2_score
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler

# define independent variables (X) and dependent variable (y)
X = merged_dfs[['danceability_%', 'valence_%', 'speechiness_%']]
y = merged_dfs['stream_change']

# initialize the scaler and standardize the independent variables
scaler = StandardScaler()
X_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X)

# split the data into training and testing sets, using train_test_split
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X_scaled, y, test_size=0.2, random_state=50)

# create the linear regression model
model = LinearRegression()
# fit the model
model.fit(X_train, y_train)

# make predictions on the test set
y_pred = model.predict(X_test)

# calculate mae
mae = (y_test - y_pred).abs().mean()
print("Mean Absolute Error:", mae)

# calculate r2
r2 = r2_score(y_test, y_pred)
print("R-squared:", r2)

Mean Absolute Error: 122371861.56929998
R-squared: 0.11288729882594617

From our model above, we see that we get a mean absolute error (MAE) of 122,371,861.57 (rounded). This shows that predictions made by your model are off by about 122 million units of the stream change (additional reading on MAE). With the range of stream change between 12,307,680 and 1,387,406,000 streams, an MAE of 122,371,861.57 streams, we get a relative measure of error of 8.9% (MAE/range). This is not great and a MAE is high which suggests that the model's predictions are not very close to the actual values. The r-squared value says that the model explains only about 11.3% of the variance in the dependent variable (stream_change). See additional reading on r-squared values.). This means that the songs attributes explain only a small fraction of the variance in stream change, and thus there might be weak relationship between danceability, valence, speechiness, and stream_change.

Lets look at a simple linear regression model that only models one independent variable, danceability, on the dependent variable, stream change. This will tell us if one attribute at a time is a better predictor of a songs stream change.

Conclusion¶

In conclusion, there is some correlaton between speechiness, danceability, valence and stream change, but there is not enough of a correlation to accurately predict a song's growth over time. This is evident by multiple and singular linear regression models, which all had high MAEs and low r-squared values, meaning the models do not provide accurate predictions. Our analysis of the data through graphs, tables, and summary statistics supports these models, as we saw in our heatmap that the correlation between the independent variables and the dependent variable was not very strong. Moreover, we dove into what songs are popular on the platformand analyzed the worst performing songs over time versus the best performing ones. We saw that in some cases, the song's shared similar statistics which lead us to believe that there are other variables at work influencing a song's growth in stream counts.

It is understandable that these three attributes are not the best predictors because of all the outside factors that affect the popularity of a song. For instance, whether the artist is on tour, its goes viral on social media, and even the artists established popularity likely influence the popularity of a song and how much it is streamed.

Examples
--------

    The simplest way to use nbconvert is

            > jupyter nbconvert mynotebook.ipynb --to html

            Options include ['asciidoc', 'custom', 'html', 'latex', 'markdown', 'notebook', 'pdf', 'python', 'qtpdf', 'qtpng', 'rst', 'script', 'slides', 'webpdf'].

            > jupyter nbconvert --to latex mynotebook.ipynb

            Both HTML and LaTeX support multiple output templates. LaTeX includes
            'base', 'article' and 'report'.  HTML includes 'basic', 'lab' and
            'classic'. You can specify the flavor of the format used.

            > jupyter nbconvert --to html --template lab mynotebook.ipynb

            You can also pipe the output to stdout, rather than a file

            > jupyter nbconvert mynotebook.ipynb --stdout

            PDF is generated via latex

            > jupyter nbconvert mynotebook.ipynb --to pdf

            You can get (and serve) a Reveal.js-powered slideshow

            > jupyter nbconvert myslides.ipynb --to slides --post serve

            Multiple notebooks can be given at the command line in a couple of
            different ways:

            > jupyter nbconvert notebook*.ipynb
            > jupyter nbconvert notebook1.ipynb notebook2.ipynb

            or you can specify the notebooks list in a config file, containing::

                c.NbConvertApp.notebooks = ["my_notebook.ipynb"]

            > jupyter nbconvert --config mycfg.py

To see all available configurables, use `--help-all`.
